The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Thursday, March 18, 2004 				 Jindal project on fast track 
 VIVEK NAIR 																								Mumbai, March 17: Jindal Power Ltd (JPL) is fast proceeding towards attaining financial closure for its 500 MW power project in Chhattisgarh. The project has received a positive response from a clutch of nationalised banks and the Industrial Development Bank of India (IDBI) for a Rs 1,500-crore loan.																								The coal-based project, promoted by Jindal Steel and Power Ltd (JSPL), part of the . P. Jindal group, will cost Rs 2,140 crore. It will have a debt-equity ratio of 70:30 and an equity base of Rs 640 crore. Jindal Steel is likely to take a 51 and 100 per cent stake in JPL. 																								Speaking to The Telegraph, Jindal Power director Sushil K. Maroo said that for the debt component, the company has received an enthusiastic response from banks. Some of the banks that are set to participate include Punjab National Bank, J amp;K Bank, State Bank of India and its associates, Canara Bank and Bank of Baroda apart from IDBI, he added.																								The debt funding is likely to be a mix of rupee and foreign currency loans and the average interest rate for JPL is likely to be between 7.5 per cent and 8 per cent. JPL is at an advanced stage of finalising the equipment. It has already received part of the land required for the project.																								We are expecting financial closure by the end of May. While larger sanctions have been received, close to Rs 500 crore is expected in April and Rs 1,000 crore in May, he said. 
